"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anywhere," justin Brookman, responsible for consumer privacy within the CDT, in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in each other, and pessimism, in others?
Biometry will be based on new technologies, which will enable new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the field of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection, as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand, involve a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - we cannot capture this data on their own - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore take time.
As a result, research has been conducted for some twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to increased sensor accuracy and the computer computing capacity necessary for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, calculated Cyrille Bataller, Director of Accenture R&D Laboratories in Europe.
With our assistance, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we do research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," said Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infalliable marker, DNA also arouses hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirmed Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC proposes to the judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples in place of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometry are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensure that the person is the person she claims to be).
The identification concerned the issue of identity papers so far: the biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has on all citizens already set.
This makes it possible to ensure that a person does not attempt to exploit someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
"We retrieve images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities that move freely on the Internet," says Dany Nassif, in charge of commercial development at NEC France for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a picture of someone who tails in a store, follow their progression through facial recognition and calculate waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (frontier, protected premises, canteens...) or logic (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control was added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the mate that points to another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But more and more authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those made from Internet-connected devices.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric player: this gesture replaces the secret code strike.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with banks and major distribution: at the time of paying in store with its bank card, the client does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If successful, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Hints to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometry attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that she can make time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in cash thirty seconds less, it's appreciated," says the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer tailored options.
And finally, make sure that the precautions taken to protect databases are highlighted.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure housing, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, without further study, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy specialists continue to worry.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, made me fear the worst: a generalized surveillance," said Andrew Patrick, from the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
